'''Mon Julpa''' {{Pronounced|mɑn 'dʒul-pʌ}} was the rightful Crown [[Prince/Legends|Prince]], later [[King/Legends|King]] of [[Tammuz-an/Legends|Tammuz-an]] during the reign of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]].

==Biography==
[[File:Mon_julpa_droid_disguise.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Mon Julpa disguised as a droid with [[Jann Tosh]] and [[R2-D2/Legends|R2-D2]]]]
[[Ko Zatec-Cha|Zatec-Cha]], a Tammuz-an [[Vizier/Legends|vizier]], brainwashed Mon, stripped him of his rule and his memory, and had his agents disguise him as an [[Android/Legends|android]]. He was sold to [[Jann Tosh]], a young miner on [[Tyne's Horky]], who discovered he was a living being. Despite the negative first reactions of his uncle [[Putch Gundarian|Gundy]], Mon worked with zeal in the mines. They nicknamed him "Kez-Iban," a [[Bocce/Legends|Bocce]] word which means "he who has returned from death."

[[Sollag Den|Sollag]] of Tammuz-an sought his prince and eventually found him and gave him back his [[Tammuz-an royal scepter|royal scepter]]. Mon Julpa's memory was restored, and he returned with Tosh and his droids to Tammuz-an in order to claim the throne that was rightfully his. After many adventures, he presented the scepter to the [[Keeper of the Tower]] at the time of the first [[Star|sun]] of the equinox and became [[King/Legends|King]] of Tammuz-an.

Julpa, after disposing of Zatec-Cha, began his efforts for uniting the two warring cultures on Tammuz-an. He approached Lord [[Malameu Toda|Toda]] of the Outer Territories to seal a treaty of peace. When pirate [[Gir Kybo Ren-Cha]] captured Toda's daughter, Princess [[Gerin Toda|Gerin]], for ransom and took her to one of the moons of [[Bogden/Legends|Bogden]], Toda and Julpa united forces to get her back. Julpa and Gerin became lovers, while Julpa and Toda became friends, uniting Tammuz-an at last.

==Behind the scenes==
Under the name Kez Iban, Mon Julpa was released as an action figure in [[1985]] as part of [[Kenner Products|Kenner's]] [[Star Wars: Droids: The Adventures of R2-D2 and C-3PO|''Star Wars Droids'']] line. These action figures were size-compatible with the other Kenner ''[[Star Wars]]'' action figures, but design-wise, they represented a different toy line. A second figure listed under the name, Mon Julpa, was prototyped and came very near to the production stage, but was never released.

Mon Julpa was voiced by [[Chris Wiggins]].

